1
00:00:03,800 --> 00:00:07,319
worca is an orchestrator for your AI coding agent.

2
00:00:07,319 --> 00:00:10,446
It runs your development process step by step.

3
00:00:10,446 --> 00:00:13,965
So the agent always starts with a design document.

4
00:00:13,965 --> 00:00:16,701
It always implements and runs the tests.

5
00:00:16,701 --> 00:00:19,047
It always performs a code review.

6
00:00:19,047 --> 00:00:20,611
Nothing important gets skipped.

7
00:00:22,411 --> 00:00:25,203
Every step runs in a fresh agent.

8
00:00:25,203 --> 00:00:29,590
That agent only sees what it needs to do its job.

9
00:00:29,590 --> 00:00:31,584
The planner sees the request.

10
00:00:31,584 --> 00:00:35,573
The implementer sees the design decisions for one code change.

11
00:00:35,573 --> 00:00:38,365
The reviewer sees the diff to review.

12
00:00:38,365 --> 00:00:39,960
Nothing leaks across stages.

13
00:00:39,960 --> 00:00:41,157
Nothing is missing.

14
00:00:41,157 --> 00:00:42,752
Each agent stays focused.

15
00:00:44,552 --> 00:00:47,254
The full flow runs as a pipeline.

16
00:00:47,254 --> 00:00:49,956
A pipeline is your workflow, written down.

17
00:00:49,956 --> 00:00:51,500
It moves through stages.

18
00:00:51,500 --> 00:00:54,202
Each stage has its own specialized agent.

19
00:00:54,202 --> 00:00:57,675
Each agent gets a prompt tailored to its role.

20
00:00:57,675 --> 00:01:02,693
And it gets a message tailored to the current state of the work.

21
00:01:02,693 --> 00:01:05,781
worca ships with several pipeline templates built in.

22
00:01:05,781 --> 00:01:08,097
You can also write your own.

23
00:01:09,897 --> 00:01:13,741
There are four ways to tell worca what to do.

24
00:01:13,741 --> 00:01:15,663
The simplest is a prompt.

25
00:01:15,663 --> 00:01:21,045
You describe the work in plain language, and the planner takes it from there.

26
00:01:21,045 --> 00:01:23,352
Next up is a GitHub issue.

27
00:01:23,352 --> 00:01:27,965
It carries more structure, and the planner uses it as a brief.

28
00:01:27,965 --> 00:01:30,656
Even richer is a pre-existing plan file.

29
00:01:30,656 --> 00:01:33,731
With that, the planner stage is skipped entirely.

30
00:01:33,731 --> 00:01:36,806
Every later stage works from your plan directly.

31
00:01:36,806 --> 00:01:40,266
The fourth input is different from the first three.

32
00:01:40,266 --> 00:01:41,804
It's called a guide.

33
00:01:41,804 --> 00:01:44,110
A guide doesn't describe the work.

34
00:01:44,110 --> 00:01:46,801
It constrains how the work is done.

35
00:01:46,801 --> 00:01:51,030
Think of an RFC, a migration spec, or a coding standard.

36
00:01:51,030 --> 00:01:54,490
Every agent treats the guide as the highest authority.

37
00:01:54,490 --> 00:01:58,334
If the plan and the guide disagree, the guide wins.

38
00:02:00,134 --> 00:02:05,573
Reading and re-reading source files is the biggest token sink in autonomous coding.

39
00:02:05,573 --> 00:02:11,431
To cut that cost, worca can build a structural knowledge graph of your repository.

40
00:02:11,431 --> 00:02:14,778
The graph captures how your code fits together.

41
00:02:14,778 --> 00:02:18,962
Agents query the graph instead of grepping their way around.

42
00:02:18,962 --> 00:02:21,054
Two engines plug in here.

43
00:02:21,054 --> 00:02:22,727
The first is graphify.

44
00:02:22,727 --> 00:02:27,330
It maps the AST and call structure of your source code.

45
00:02:27,330 --> 00:02:29,003
The second is CRG.

46
00:02:29,003 --> 00:02:35,279
CRG runs in structural mode today, and a richer semantic mode is on the roadmap.

47
00:02:35,279 --> 00:02:37,789
Either way, the graph is advisory.

48
00:02:37,789 --> 00:02:40,718
It never overrides what you asked for.

49
00:02:40,718 --> 00:02:44,902
It just helps the agents find their way around faster.
